1) Why do we convert continuous values into categories?
We convert continuous values into categories to make the data easier to understand and analyze.
Instead of dealing with many numbers, we group them into meaningful labels like Gold, Silver, and Bronze, which are easier for business teams to interpret.

2) Difference between business segmentation and technical bucketing
Business Segmentation:
Based on fixed business rules
Example: Customers spending more than 100 = Gold
Technical Bucketing:
Based on data distribution or algorithms
Example: Dividing customers using quantiles or bucketizer

3) When do fixed thresholds fail?
Fixed thresholds fail when the data distribution changes.
For example:
If most customers spend very high or very low, then:
One segment may have too many customers
Other segments may have very few
This makes the segmentation unbalanced and less useful.

4) Difference between quantile-based segmentation and fixed rules
Fixed Rules:
Use predefined values (e.g., >500 = High)
Quantile-Based Segmentation:
Divides data into equal-sized groups based on distribution
This ensures all segments have a balanced number of customers.

5) Which method would you use in real-world projects?
It depends on the situation:
Use business rules when requirements are clearly defined
Use quantile or ranking methods when you want data-driven and balanced segmentation
